# ======================= BENGALURU =======================

P(slug="lalbagh-bengaluru", city="Bengaluru", region="Karnataka", cat="Garden & Park",
  name="Lalbagh Botanical Garden", query="Lalbagh Bangalore",
  excerpt="Bengaluru's magnificent 240-acre botanical garden — a 200-year-old green lung with a glass house, a lake and ancient trees.",
  tags=["Bengaluru","garden","nature","heritage"],
  info=dict(timings="6 AM – 7 PM (daily)", entry="Nominal (approx ₹20–₹50)",
            best="Early morning; flower shows in Jan & Aug", duration="1.5–2 hours", reach="South Bengaluru; nearest Metro Lalbagh"),
  body="""<p>Begun in the 18th century under Hyder Ali and Tipu Sultan, Lalbagh is the green soul of Bengaluru — 240 acres of manicured lawns, ancient trees, a picturesque lake and one of the largest collections of tropical plants in India. It embodies the city's old identity as the 'Garden City'.</p>
<p>Its centrepiece is the grand Glass House, modelled on London's Crystal Palace, which hosts spectacular flower shows twice a year. A 3,000-million-year-old rock formation and a lakeside dotted with birds add to the appeal of this beloved civic space.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The iconic Glass House and its biannual flower shows.</li><li>The ancient trees and the peaceful lake.</li><li>The Lalbagh Rock, among the oldest on earth.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Mornings are cool, quiet and full of birdsong and joggers. A refreshing break from the city's traffic.</p>""")

P(slug="bangalore-palace", city="Bengaluru", region="Karnataka", cat="Palace & Fort",
  name="Bangalore Palace", query="Bangalore Palace",
  excerpt="A Tudor-style royal palace of turrets and grand halls — a slice of English fantasy in the heart of the Garden City.",
  tags=["Bengaluru","palace","heritage","royal"],
  info=dict(timings="10 AM – 5:30 PM (daily)", entry="Approx ₹230 (Indian) / ₹460 (foreign); camera charge extra",
            best="Morning", duration="1–1.5 hours", reach="Central Bengaluru, Vasanth Nagar"),
  body="""<p>Inspired by England's Windsor Castle, Bangalore Palace is a surprising vision of Tudor-revival architecture — fortified towers, battlements, arches and grand fresco-filled halls — built by the Wodeyar dynasty in the late 19th century. It's still owned by the royal family of Mysore.</p>
<p>The opulent interiors, with their carvings, paintings, and vintage furniture, offer a glimpse into royal life, while the extensive grounds host major concerts and events. An audio guide walks you through its history and treasures.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The Tudor-style turrets and battlements.</li><li>The ornate Durbar Hall and painted interiors.</li><li>The royal portraits and vintage furnishings.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>There's a separate (higher) charge for cameras. The audio guide adds context. The grounds often host big-name concerts — check what's on.</p>""")

P(slug="brigade-road-bengaluru", city="Bengaluru", region="Karnataka", cat="Nightlife",
  name="MG Road & Brigade Road", query="Brigade Road Bangalore",
  excerpt="The buzzing commercial and nightlife core of Bengaluru — shopping by day, pubs, breweries and live music by night in India's pub capital.",
  tags=["Bengaluru","nightlife","pubs","shopping"],
  info=dict(timings="Shops from late morning; pubs & clubs till late", entry="Free to explore; venues priced individually",
            best="Evening into night", duration="An evening", reach="Central Bengaluru; nearest Metro MG Road / Trinity"),
  body="""<p>The intersection of MG Road and Brigade Road is the throbbing centre of Bengaluru's social life. Long known as India's 'pub capital', the city practically invented the modern Indian nightlife scene here, and this area remains its beating heart — dense with pubs, microbreweries, rooftop bars, live-music venues and restaurants.</p>
<p>By day it's a shopping and café hub; by night the whole district hums with a young, cosmopolitan crowd. Nearby Church Street and Indiranagar extend the scene, but Brigade Road is where Bengaluru's love of a good night out began.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The craft microbreweries — a Bengaluru speciality.</li><li>Live-music nights and rooftop bars.</li><li>Church Street's cafés, bookshops and eateries.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Bengaluru's nightlife can wind down earlier than Mumbai or Delhi — start your evening on time. Indiranagar is the other big nightlife hub worth exploring.</p>""")

P(slug="vv-puram-food-street-bengaluru", city="Bengaluru", region="Karnataka", cat="Food Street",
  name="VV Puram Food Street", query="VV Puram food street Bangalore",
  excerpt="Bengaluru's beloved 'Thindi Beedi' — a compact lane of sizzling vegetarian street food that comes alive every evening.",
  tags=["Bengaluru","street food","vegetarian","food"],
  info=dict(timings="Evenings, roughly 5 PM – midnight", entry="Free (pay as you eat)",
            best="Evening; come hungry", duration="1.5–2 hours", reach="VV Puram, south Bengaluru, near Sajjan Rao Circle"),
  body="""<p>Every evening, a short lane in the old district of VV Puram transforms into Bengaluru's most famous food street — known affectionately as 'Thindi Beedi' (Snack Street). Stalls fire up their griddles and cauldrons to serve a dizzying array of South Indian and North Indian vegetarian street food.</p>
<p>Wander from stall to stall sampling crisp dosas, gooey holige, butter-laden akki roti, deep-fried delights and hot jalebis, finishing with a paan. It's affordable, entirely vegetarian, and a joyful crash course in local flavours.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>Dosas, holige (sweet flatbread) and butter-drenched snacks.</li><li>The deep-fried specialities and hot jalebis.</li><li>A traditional paan to finish.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>It's an evening affair and entirely vegetarian. Small plates mean you can graze across many stalls — go with an appetite and a group.</p>""")

P(slug="commercial-street-bengaluru", city="Bengaluru", region="Karnataka", cat="Street & Bazaar",
  name="Commercial Street", query="Commercial Street Bangalore",
  excerpt="Bengaluru's oldest and busiest shopping strip — a chaotic, colourful maze of fashion, jewellery, fabrics and bargains.",
  tags=["Bengaluru","shopping","market","street"],
  info=dict(timings="Roughly 11 AM – 9 PM (some shops closed Sundays)", entry="Free",
            best="Weekday afternoons (weekends are packed)", duration="2–3 hours", reach="Central Bengaluru, near MG Road / Shivajinagar"),
  body="""<p>One of Bengaluru's oldest retail districts, Commercial Street is a shopper's playground — a dense grid of lanes crammed with shops and stalls selling clothing, footwear, jewellery, fabrics, accessories and electronics, from budget bargains to bridal finery.</p>
<p>The energy is relentless and the choice overwhelming: high-street stores sit beside tiny family shops and pavement vendors, all buzzing with hagglers. It's the place to shop till you drop and then refuel at the area's famous street food and old-school eateries.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>Bargaining for clothes, footwear and jewellery.</li><li>The fabric and ethnic-wear shops.</li><li>The street food and heritage cafés nearby.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Weekends are extremely crowded — go on a weekday. Carry cash for the small stalls and be ready to haggle.</p>""")

# ======================= HYDERABAD =======================

P(slug="charminar-hyderabad", city="Hyderabad", region="Telangana", cat="Landmark",
  name="Charminar", query="Charminar Hyderabad",
  excerpt="Hyderabad's iconic four-minaret monument — the 16th-century heart of the old city, ringed by the glittering Laad Bazaar.",
  tags=["Hyderabad","landmark","Mughal","icon"],
  info=dict(timings="Approx 9:30 AM – 5:30 PM", entry="Approx ₹25 (Indian) / ₹300 (foreign)",
            best="Morning, or evening when it's lit up", duration="1 hour (plus bazaar)", reach="Old city, Hyderabad"),
  body="""<p>The Charminar is Hyderabad — a majestic square monument with four soaring minarets, built in 1591 to mark the founding of the city. Its graceful arches and intricate stucco work anchor the historic old city, and it's as central to Hyderabad's identity as the Taj is to Agra.</p>
<p>Around its base swirls one of India's great bazaars, and the monument is at its most magical in the evening when floodlit. Climb up for views over the teeming old city and the nearby Mecca Masjid.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The four-minaret monument, floodlit after dark.</li><li>The surrounding Laad Bazaar and Mecca Masjid.</li><li>The views over the old city from the upper level.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>The old-city lanes are congested — go on foot. Combine with Laad Bazaar shopping and Hyderabad's legendary biryani nearby.</p>""")

P(slug="golconda-fort-hyderabad", city="Hyderabad", region="Telangana", cat="Palace & Fort",
  name="Golconda Fort", query="Golconda Fort Hyderabad",
  excerpt="A colossal hilltop citadel famed for its acoustics, diamonds and grandeur — and a spectacular evening sound-and-light show.",
  tags=["Hyderabad","fort","history","viewpoint"],
  info=dict(timings="9 AM – 5:30 PM; evening light & sound show", entry="Approx ₹25 (Indian) / ₹300 (foreign)",
            best="Late afternoon; stay for the show", duration="2–3 hours", reach="Western Hyderabad, ~11 km from the centre"),
  body="""<p>Once the capital of a powerful sultanate and the centre of the world's diamond trade — the Koh-i-Noor passed through here — Golconda Fort is a massive citadel rising on a granite hill west of Hyderabad. Its concentric fortifications, palaces, mosques and gardens sprawl across the slopes.</p>
<p>The fort is famous for its ingenious engineering: a clap at the entrance dome can be heard at the hilltop pavilion nearly a kilometre away, an acoustic early-warning system. Climb to the top for sweeping views, and stay for the evening sound-and-light show narrating its dramatic history.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The famous acoustics at the Fateh Darwaza gate.</li><li>The climb to the Bala Hisar pavilion and its views.</li><li>The evening sound-and-light show.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>It's a fair climb — wear good shoes and carry water. Late afternoon lets you explore then catch the show. The nearby Qutb Shahi tombs pair well with a visit.</p>""")

P(slug="laad-bazaar-hyderabad", city="Hyderabad", region="Telangana", cat="Street & Bazaar",
  name="Laad Bazaar", query="Laad Bazaar Hyderabad",
  excerpt="The dazzling centuries-old market around Charminar — famous for lacquer bangles, pearls, bridal wear and old-city buzz.",
  tags=["Hyderabad","market","bangles","shopping"],
  info=dict(timings="Roughly 11 AM – 9 PM (Fridays quieter)", entry="Free",
            best="Late afternoon into evening", duration="1.5–2 hours", reach="Old city, flanking the Charminar"),
  body="""<p>Radiating from the Charminar, Laad Bazaar is one of Hyderabad's oldest and most colourful markets — a centuries-old bazaar most famous for its glittering lacquer bangles studded with stones, a must-buy for brides across the region. The lanes glow with colour and sparkle.</p>
<p>Beyond bangles, the market overflows with pearls (Hyderabad is India's pearl capital), bridal finery, perfumes, fabrics and traditional jewellery. Shopping here, in the shadow of the Charminar, is a feast for the senses.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The signature lacquer-and-stone bangles.</li><li>Hyderabadi pearls and traditional jewellery.</li><li>The bridal wear, perfumes and old-city atmosphere.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Bargaining is expected. The lanes are narrow and crowded — go on foot and mind your belongings. Best combined with a Charminar visit and a biryani stop.</p>""")

P(slug="hyderabad-biryani-food", city="Hyderabad", region="Telangana", cat="Food Street",
  name="Hyderabadi biryani & old-city eats", query="Hyderabadi biryani",
  excerpt="The city that gave India its most famous biryani — a legendary food scene of dum biryani, haleem, kebabs and Irani chai.",
  tags=["Hyderabad","biryani","food","Nizami"],
  info=dict(timings="Lunch is prime biryani time; haleem in Ramadan evenings", entry="Free (pay as you eat)",
            best="Lunch for biryani; Ramadan for haleem", duration="A meal (or a food crawl)", reach="Old-city eateries and city-wide institutions"),
  body="""<p>No Indian city is more synonymous with a single dish than Hyderabad and its biryani. Born in the kitchens of the Nizams, Hyderabadi dum biryani — fragrant basmati and marinated meat slow-cooked together under a sealed lid — is a national obsession, and the city is full of legendary institutions serving it.</p>
<p>But the Nizami food legacy runs deeper: melt-in-the-mouth haleem (a Ramadan speciality), rich kebabs, nihari, and the beloved ritual of Irani chai with Osmania biscuits in the city's old cafés. Eating your way through Hyderabad is a highlight in itself.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>Authentic Hyderabadi dum biryani.</li><li>Haleem, especially during Ramadan.</li><li>Irani chai and Osmania biscuits at a heritage café.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Biryani is best at lunch when it's freshest. Haleem is a seasonal Ramadan treat. Ask locals for their favourite institution — everyone has strong opinions.</p>""")

# ======================= CHENNAI =======================

P(slug="marina-beach-chennai", city="Chennai", region="Tamil Nadu", cat="Beach",
  name="Marina Beach", query="Marina Beach Chennai",
  excerpt="One of the world's longest urban beaches — a vast golden sweep where all of Chennai gathers at dawn and dusk.",
  tags=["Chennai","beach","promenade","sunrise"],
  info=dict(timings="Open all day; liveliest at dawn and evening", entry="Free",
            best="Sunrise or evening (swimming is unsafe)", duration="1–2 hours", reach="Along the Bay of Bengal, central Chennai"),
  body="""<p>Stretching along the Bay of Bengal, Marina Beach is one of the longest urban beaches in the world and the great public space of Chennai. It's not a swimming beach — strong currents make that dangerous — but a place for the whole city to walk, play, fly kites and eat as the sun rises or sets.</p>
<p>The wide promenade is lined with statues, historic buildings and food stalls serving local favourites like sundal and bajji. At dawn, joggers and fishermen share the sand; by evening, it becomes a lively carnival.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>Sunrise over the Bay of Bengal.</li><li>Beach snacks — sundal, bajji and fresh fruit.</li><li>The historic buildings and statues along the promenade.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Do not swim — the currents are dangerous. It's for strolling and snacking, not bathing. Mornings and evenings are the pleasant times in Chennai's heat.</p>""")

P(slug="kapaleeshwarar-temple-chennai", city="Chennai", region="Tamil Nadu", cat="Temple",
  name="Kapaleeshwarar Temple", query="Kapaleeshwarar Temple Chennai",
  excerpt="Chennai's most important temple — a riot of colourful Dravidian sculpture crowning the atmospheric Mylapore district.",
  tags=["Chennai","temple","Dravidian","Mylapore"],
  info=dict(timings="Approx 5 AM – 12 PM & 4 PM – 9 PM", entry="Free",
            best="Early morning or evening; festival season is spectacular", duration="1 hour", reach="Mylapore, central Chennai"),
  body="""<p>Rising above the historic Mylapore neighbourhood, the Kapaleeshwarar Temple is Chennai's spiritual heart — a classic example of Dravidian architecture dedicated to Lord Shiva. Its towering gopuram (gateway tower) is a dazzling, riotously colourful pyramid of carved deities and figures.</p>
<p>Inside, the temple is alive with ritual, music and the scent of jasmine and incense. The surrounding Mylapore district — with its traditional houses, flower markets and the temple tank — is one of the most atmospheric corners of the city.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The vividly painted, sculpture-covered gopuram.</li><li>The temple tank and the old Mylapore streets.</li><li>The colour and energy of festival days, if your timing aligns.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Remove shoes and dress respectfully. Non-Hindus are welcome in most areas. Mylapore's flower market and filter coffee spots make a lovely add-on.</p>""")

P(slug="fort-st-george-chennai", city="Chennai", region="Tamil Nadu", cat="Landmark",
  name="Fort St George", query="Fort St George Chennai",
  excerpt="The first English fortress in India and the birthplace of modern Chennai — now a museum and the seat of the state government.",
  tags=["Chennai","colonial","history","fort"],
  info=dict(timings="Museum ~9 AM – 5 PM (closed Fridays)", entry="Museum approx ₹15 (Indian) / ₹200 (foreign)",
            best="Morning", duration="1–1.5 hours", reach="Near Marina Beach and the harbour, central Chennai"),
  body="""<p>Built in 1644, Fort St George was the first English fortress in India and the seed from which the city of Madras — now Chennai — grew. Today it houses the Tamil Nadu state legislature alongside a fascinating museum of the colonial era.</p>
<p>Within its walls stand St Mary's Church, the oldest surviving Anglican church east of Suez, and the Fort Museum, whose collection of weapons, uniforms, coins and portraits tells the story of early British India. It's a compact, history-rich stop near the seafront.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The Fort Museum's colonial-era collection.</li><li>St Mary's Church, the oldest Anglican church in India.</li><li>The old fort walls and their harbour setting.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>It's an active government complex, so carry ID and expect security checks. The museum is closed on Fridays. Easily combined with Marina Beach.</p>""")

P(slug="t-nagar-chennai", city="Chennai", region="Tamil Nadu", cat="Street & Bazaar",
  name="T. Nagar (shopping)", query="T Nagar Chennai shopping",
  excerpt="One of India's busiest shopping districts — a frenetic hub of silk sarees, gold jewellery and everything else, especially at festival time.",
  tags=["Chennai","shopping","silk","market"],
  info=dict(timings="Roughly 10 AM – 9 PM", entry="Free",
            best="Weekday mornings (festival season is chaos)", duration="2–3 hours", reach="Thyagaraya Nagar, central Chennai"),
  body="""<p>T. Nagar (Thyagaraya Nagar) is one of the highest-revenue shopping districts in the country and the retail engine of Chennai. Centred on Ranganathan Street and Pondy Bazaar, it's a dense, frantic warren of enormous silk and jewellery emporiums, textile showrooms and pavement stalls.</p>
<p>The area is legendary for silk sarees and gold — Chennai families flock here for weddings and festivals — and the crowds during Diwali or the wedding season are a spectacle in themselves. It's chaotic, colourful and quintessentially Chennai.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The grand silk saree and textile emporiums.</li><li>The gold and jewellery showrooms.</li><li>Pondy Bazaar's street stalls and snacks.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Avoid festival-season weekends unless you love crowds. It's walkable but intense — go early. Fixed-price emporiums sit alongside hagglable street stalls.</p>""")

# ======================= MYSURU =======================

P(slug="mysore-palace", city="Mysuru", region="Karnataka", cat="Palace & Fort",
  name="Mysore Palace", query="Mysore Palace",
  excerpt="One of India's grandest royal palaces — an Indo-Saracenic fantasy that blazes with nearly 100,000 lights every Sunday night.",
  tags=["Mysuru","palace","royal","illumination"],
  info=dict(timings="10 AM – 5:30 PM; illumination Sun & holidays ~7–7:45 PM", entry="Approx ₹100 (Indian) / ₹200 (foreign)",
            best="Sunday evening for the light show; Dasara festival", duration="1.5–2 hours", reach="Central Mysuru, ~3 hrs from Bengaluru"),
  body="""<p>The seat of the Wodeyar dynasty, Mysore Palace is among the most magnificent royal residences in India — a dazzling Indo-Saracenic confection of domes, arches, turrets and stained glass, rebuilt in the early 20th century. Its interiors are a riot of ornate halls, carved doors, mosaic floors and royal splendour.</p>
<p>The palace is at its most spectacular after dark: every Sunday and on public holidays, it's outlined by nearly 100,000 light bulbs that transform it into a glowing jewel. During the grand Dasara festival, Mysuru and its palace become the centre of one of India's most famous celebrations.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The palace ablaze with lights on Sunday evenings.</li><li>The opulent Durbar Hall and Kalyana Mantapa (marriage pavilion).</li><li>The Dasara festivities, if you visit in autumn.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Shoes must be removed inside (deposit provided). Photography is restricted in the interior halls. Time your visit for a Sunday evening if you can, for the illumination.</p>""")

P(slug="chamundi-hill-mysuru", city="Mysuru", region="Karnataka", cat="Temple",
  name="Chamundi Hill", query="Chamundi Hill Mysore",
  excerpt="A sacred hilltop temple above Mysuru with panoramic views, a giant monolithic Nandi bull and 1,000 pilgrim steps.",
  tags=["Mysuru","temple","viewpoint","pilgrimage"],
  info=dict(timings="Temple approx 7:30 AM – 9 PM (with breaks)", entry="Free (special darshan tickets available)",
            best="Early morning for views and fewer crowds", duration="1.5–2 hours", reach="~13 km from Mysuru; drive up or climb 1,000 steps"),
  body="""<p>Rising above Mysuru, Chamundi Hill is crowned by the Sri Chamundeshwari Temple, dedicated to the goddess after whom the hill is named and revered as the patron deity of the Mysore royal family. The climb — or drive — up is rewarded with sweeping views over the city and palace below.</p>
<p>The devout ascend the roughly 1,000 stone steps, passing the huge monolithic Nandi (the sacred bull) carved from a single rock partway up. The colourful temple gopuram and the hilltop panorama make it a rewarding half-day trip.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The views over Mysuru from the summit.</li><li>The giant monolithic Nandi bull on the steps.</li><li>The ornate Chamundeshwari Temple gopuram.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>You can drive up or climb the steps (barefoot for the devout). Mornings are cooler and clearer. Queues at the temple can be long on weekends and festival days.</p>""")

P(slug="devaraja-market-mysuru", city="Mysuru", region="Karnataka", cat="Street & Bazaar",
  name="Devaraja Market", query="Devaraja Market Mysore",
  excerpt="A vibrant, century-old bazaar bursting with flowers, fruit, spices and Mysuru's famous sandalwood and incense.",
  tags=["Mysuru","market","flowers","spices"],
  info=dict(timings="Roughly 6 AM – 8:30 PM", entry="Free",
            best="Morning, when the flowers are fresh", duration="1 hour", reach="Central Mysuru, near the palace"),
  body="""<p>In the heart of Mysuru, the Devaraja Market has been trading for well over a century — a bustling, photogenic bazaar under a warren of stalls piled high with pyramids of kumkum powder, mounds of fragrant flowers, fresh fruit and vegetables, spices, and the region's celebrated sandalwood products and incense.</p>
<p>It's a feast for the senses and a wonderful window into everyday Mysuru life, with vendors happy to pose amid their colourful wares. A great place to buy incense, sandalwood soap and spices to take home.</p>
<h2>Don't miss</h2>
<ul><li>The dazzling flower and kumkum stalls.</li><li>Mysuru sandalwood products, incense and spices.</li><li>The fresh-fruit and produce sections.</li></ul>
<h2>Good to know</h2>
<p>Mornings are freshest and most colourful. Vendors may expect a small tip for photos. It's a short walk from Mysore Palace.</p>""")
